## Summary of MTCars Dataset

Few of the variables are marked with specific names to comprehend data effectively. "am" variable is marked with "Auto" if value is 0 and "Manual" on the off chance that it is 1. Likewise, "cyl" variable has given values "Small", "Medium", "Large" depends on number of cylinders. Following table showcases six records from MTCars dataset. 

Please note that the data in the table uses name abbreviations such as "am" which marks wether the car is manual vs automatic. We also hav "cyl" which represents "cylinder" and has the values of large, med and small. 

\newpage

## Data Analysis on MTcars dataset
Number of automatic and manual cars and their proportion
```{r mtcars}
cars_auto = subset(mtcars, am == 0)
cars_auto_str = paste('Automatic: ', nrow(cars_auto))
cars_auto_str_prop = paste('Automatic Proportion: ', 
                           nrow(cars_auto)/nrow(mtcars))

cars_manual = subset(mtcars, am == 1)
cars_manual_str = paste('Manual: ', nrow(cars_manual))
cars_manual_str_prop = paste('Manual Proportion: ', 
                             nrow(cars_manual)/nrow(mtcars))
print(cars_auto_str)
print(cars_auto_str_prop)
print(cars_manual_str)
print(cars_manual_str_prop)
```

## Histogram for MPG of cars
This distribution is approx. normal

```{r mpg}
histmpg <- hist(mtcars$mpg, breaks=10, xlab = "Miles per gallon", 
     main = "Historgram of Miles per gallon of cars", xlim = range(10:35))
lines(density(mtcars$mpg))
```

## MPG by transmission type
It appears that manual transmission comes ahead in terms of MPG
```{r histtransmission} 
histtr <- plot(mtcars$mpg ~ as.factor(mtcars$am), mtcars, 
     xlab = "Transmission type", ylab="Miles per gallon", 
     main="Histogram of MPG by transmission type")
```


## MPG Histogram based on weight of car
Weight of the car is inversly pproprtional to mileage. 
```{r weight}
wt= cut(mtcars$wt, 3, labels = c("Small-Size","Med-Size","Large-Size"))
histwt <-hist(mtcars$wt, xlab="Mileage", 
     main="Mileage of engine based on weight", col="green")
```

```{r plots}
print(histmpg, split = c(1, 1, 2, 2), more = TRUE)

print(histtr, split = c(2, 1, 2, 2), more = TRUE)

print(histwt, split = c(1, 2, 2, 2), more = FALSE)

```

\newpage
## MPG and transmission 
The result suggests that manual cars have better mpg
```{r, echo=TRUE, results='asis', fig.height=4, fig.width=4}
aovam= aov(mtcars$mpg ~ factor(am), 
           data=mtcars)
model.tables(aovam, type="effects")
```

## MPG and cylinders
The result suggests that the number of cylinders of the smaller cars make them more gas efficent.
```{r, echo=TRUE, results='asis', fig.height=4, fig.width=4}
aovcyl= aov(mtcars$mpg ~ factor(mtcars$cyl), 
            data=mtcars)
model.tables(aovcyl, type="effects")
```

## MPG and gear
The result suggests that cars with 4 gears are better (in terms of mpg) than the ones with less gears
```{r, echo=TRUE, results='asis', fig.height=4, fig.width=4}
aovgear= aov(mtcars$mpg ~ factor(mtcars$gear), 
             data=mtcars)
model.tables(aovgear, type="effects")
```

## MPG and weight
The result suggests smaller (lower weight) cars have better mpg

```{r, echo=TRUE, results='asis', fig.height=4, fig.width=4}
wtfactor= factor(wt, 
                 levels= c("Small-Size","Med-Size","Large-Size")
                 , labels = c("Small","Medium","Large"))
aovwt= aov(mtcars$mpg ~ wtfactor, data=mtcars)
model.tables(aovwt, type="effects")
```

\newpage

## Linear Model Analysis
```{r, echo=TRUE, results='asis', fig.height=4, fig.width=4}
Model <- lm(mtcars$mpg ~ mtcars$wt, data=mtcars)
coef.Model <- coef(Model)
coef.Model
plot(mtcars$mpg ~ mtcars$wt, data=mtcars, 
     ylab="Mileage", xlab="Weight of Car")
abline(coef=coef.Model)
```

\newpage
## Summary
This research paper reached a number of conclusions (based on the provided dataset):
- Cars with manual tranmission has a better mpg than manual cars
- Cars with less cylinders have better mpg than manual cars
- Cars with 4 gears have better mpg than cars with a lower number of gears
- Cars with lower weight have better mpg
